{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":9973,"record_hash":"sha256:ecd14497de63f91a01a07cd3fb3cfefa2637e3d1ead2bd7a047945beb9a16dd3","timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:44:04.294Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: f772e0\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1195\nOutput:\n- stable ids and links across rebases or branch movement\n- reindexable derived stores if we add local acceleration later\n\nIt should not copy these:\n\n- provider-native resume semantics for cross-provider handoff\n- automatic ingestion of all related transcript records\n- persistent generated summaries as the only source of truth\n- one magic `handoff` command that hides the read path\n- cryptographic provenance or SLSA-style ceremony for v1\n\n## Minimal Tool Draft\n\nThe minimal agent-facing surface should be three read tools:\n\n```text\nbut agentlog sessions [branch <branch> | review <review> | change <change>] [--limit N]\nbut agentlog timeline <session-key> [--limit N]\nbut agentlog records <session-key> --turn <turn-key> [--from start|end|<index>] [--limit N]\n```\n\nThis is enough for an agent to:\n\n1. discover prior sessions\n2. orient itself in the session and turn structure\n3. read bounded transcript records only where needed\n\nThere should not be a first-class `handoff` command. Handoff is the workflow the\nagent performs with these tools.\n\n### `sessions`\n\nPurpose: answer \"what sessions should I inspect?\"\n\nTargeted form:\n\n```text\nbut agentlog sessions branch agentlog-turn-storage\n```\n\nUntargeted form:\n\n```text\nbut agentlog sessions --limit 10\n```\n\nThe targeted form returns sessions related to a branch, review, or change. The\nuntargeted form returns recent project sessions. Both should return compact\norientation data.\n\nJSON should include:\n\n- requested target, if any\n- `session_key`\n- `updated_at`\n- `turn_count`\n- `record_count`\n- `related_turn_keys`, only for targeted lookup\n- source metadata: agents, providers, models, tool versions\n- latest turn key and latest capture timestamp\n\nThis command should not hydrate transcript records. It is an index card.\n\n### `timeline`\n\nPurpose: answer \"what happened across this session, and which turns look worth\nreading?\"\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nbut agentlog timeline sha256-9d942495a\n[TRUNCATED]\nordered transcript records\n- record index/range metadata\n- `next` and `previous` cursors or offsets when more records are available\n\nThe command must be bounded by default. Backfilled turns can contain thousands\nof records, so `records` should never accidentally dump a whole historical\nsession because one turn was large. If the agent needs more, it can read the\nnext or previous range.\n\n`--from end` matters. For handoff, the latest records in a huge backfill are\nusually more useful than the oldest records. The oldest records can still matter\nfor the original task prompt, so `--from start` should remain available.\n\nThe first version should not add record-kind filtering. Return ordered records\nwith clear `kind`, `role`, `tool_name`, and redacted text fields. The consuming\nagent can decide to skim tool calls, skip noisy tool results, or read them when\ntests/errors/commands matter.\n\n## Expected Agent Access Pattern\n\nWhen a user asks an agent to catch up with a branch, the agent should not try to\nload everything. A good workflow is:\n\n1. Resolve the current branch or requested branch.\n2. Run `but agentlog sessions branch <branch>`.\n3. Pick likely useful sessions from outline data:\n   - prefer recent sessions\n   - prefer sessions with incremental turns over one-off sidecar backfills\n   - inspect sidecar sessions only when their previews look relevant\n4. Run `but agentlog timeline <session-key> --limit 20` for the most promising\n   session.\n5. Read records from selected turns:\n   - latest incremental turns first\n   - tail of a large backfill when the backfill is the only evidence\n   - head of a backfill only if the original task prompt is unclear\n6. Read adjacent or older turns only if the first pass leaves gaps.\n\nThe agent's natural unit of navigation is the capture turn, not individual\nrecords. Records are the rendering layer once a turn has been selected.\n\nTool calls and tool results should stay visible but not dominate the workflow.\nIn practice, the agent should scan:\n\n- user messages for intent and corrections\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:44:04.294Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}